Publication_Title: Litter breakdown and invertebrate association with three types of leaves in a temperate rainforest stream
Notes: Water from Mayfly Creek was diverted into experimental stream channels - 14m long and about 25 cm wide with a slope of approximately 0.03m/m. Leaf packets were placed in mesh boxes inside of the channels. Mesh size was 0.48 mm except for the upstream side where the mesh size was 1mm. On the upstream side of the mesh box was a 2 cm opening that also allowed invertebrates to move in and out of the box. Nutrient values were analyzed only in two times: d0 and d39 /d43. I did not collect data on water variables because they are from another study in another year (1979).

Rapid breakdown of allochthonous and autochthonous plant material in a eutrophic river
Geog_Locale: Snake River, Twin Falls, Idaho, USA
Notes: The objective of this study was to determine whether differences existed between decomposition of autochthonous macrophytes (breakdown measured in spring and fall) and allocthonous litter (breakdown measured only in July). Water chem: Converted mg/L SRP to ug/L. No initial mass provided; paper says leaves were divided into samples, but does not report how much in each bag. Authors report sample size of "three to four bags"- I note only the more conservative number since they do not specify.
